To prove in fact there is a stronger proposition:
$$\begin{array}{c}
\left(a_{1}, a_{2}, \cdots, a_{n}\right)>\left(b_{1}, b_{2}, \cdots, b_{n}\right) \\
\sum_{i=1}^{n-1} a_{i}-\sum_{i=1}^{n-1} b_{i} \geqslant\left(\sum_{i=1}^{n-1} \frac{a_{i}}{b_{i}}-n+1\right) b_{n}
\end{array}$$

We use mathematical induction to prove this proposition. When $k=1$, it is obviously true. Assume that when $n=k$, the proposition holds. When $k+1$, by the condition we have
$$a_{k+1} \geqslant\left(k+1-\sum_{i=1}^{k} \frac{a_{i}}{b_{i}}\right) b_{k+1}$$

According to the induction hypothesis, $\sum_{i=1}^{j} a_{i} \geqslant \sum_{i=1}^{j} b_{i} (j=1,2, \cdots, k)$, so
$$\begin{array}{l}
\left(a_{1}, a_{2}, \cdots, a_{k+1}\right)>\left(b_{1}, b_{2}, \cdots, b_{k+1}\right) \Leftarrow \\
\sum_{i=1}^{n} a_{i}+\left(k+1-\sum_{i=1}^{k} \frac{a_{i}}{b_{i}}\right) b_{k+1} \geqslant \sum_{i=1}^{k+1} b_{i} \Leftrightarrow \\
\sum_{i=1}^{k} a_{i}-\sum_{i=1}^{k} b_{i} \geqslant\left(\sum_{i=1}^{k} \frac{a_{i}}{b_{i}}-k\right) b_{k+1}
\end{array}$$

Notice that the above is another inequality to be proven, $b_{k+1} \geqslant b_{k}$, so we only need to prove
$$\begin{array}{l}
\sum_{i=1}^{k} a_{i}-\sum_{i=1}^{k} b_{i} \geqslant\left(\sum_{i=1}^{k} \frac{a_{i}}{b_{i}}-k\right) b_{k} \Leftrightarrow \\
\sum_{i=1}^{k-1} a_{i}-\sum_{i=1}^{k-1} b_{i} \geqslant\left(\sum_{i=1}^{k-1} \frac{a_{i}}{b_{i}}-k+1\right) b_{k}
\end{array}$$

The above is proven by the induction hypothesis! Therefore, the proposition holds for any natural number $n$, and the original proposition is proven!

